erings (8th–6th centuries BC) / Commensalité en Sicile occidentale – le foyer comme point focal des rituels pour les rassemblements sociaux (viiie–vie s. av. J.-C.) -- tSouth of France -- tLes foyers domestiques de l’Âge du fer dans le Sud de la France (viie–ier s. av. J.-C.). Objets utilitaires ou symboliques ? / Domestic hearths of the Iron Age in the South of France (7th–1st centuries BC). Functional or symbolic objects? -- tIberian Peninsula -- tForme, fonction et signification des foyers dans la culture ibérique (600–200 av. J.-C.) / Shape, function and significance of hearths in the Iberian culture (600–200 BC) -- tConclusion: building a fireplace to build a world -- tIndex: English words -- tIndex: French words -- tIndex of Toponyms0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFrom basic needs, such as lighting, heating or cooking, to symbolic or ritual engagement, hearths in indoor contexts serve as a focal point. This is especially evident, both spatially and architecturally, in structures containing central hearths. In assessing any gathering around a hearth, the types of social groups involved need to be determined and their interactions clearly assessed in each specific case. Beyond clearly domestic contexts, many rooms or buildings have been deemed religious or cultic places often based solely on the presence of a hearth, despite other possible interpretations. This volume appraises and contextualises diversity in practice centering on the hearth in the Aegean and, more widely, in areas of the Western Mediterranean closely connected to Greek civilization, notably through its colonies, revealing surprising similarities but also local adaptations. In the West, the use of the hearth often has a unique character arising from local adaptations born of indigenous practices. The combined approach presented here, detailing technical aspects of the hearths themselves, their architectural settings and any associated artefacts or furnishings, affords a rich spectrum for cross-cultural analysis between these Mediterranean regions.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aIron agezMediterranean Region. 4aAltar. 4aEisenzeit. 4aHerd. 4aÄgäis. 7aHISTORY / Medieval.2bisacsh  aHearths, Hearth-altars, Ritual Dining, Indoor sacrifice.1 aBastide, Maguelone, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBastide, Maguelone, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBelarte, Maria Carme, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChazelles, Claire-Anne de, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEkroth, Gunnel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKrasteva, Zornitsa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLamaze, Jérémy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLamaze, Jérémy, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aRivière, Karine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSimantoni-Bournia, Evangelia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aÖhlinger, Birgit, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Ebook Package English 2021z978311075072008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus DeG Package 2021 Part 1z978311075070608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021 Englishz978311075400108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021z9783110753776oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Classical Studies 2021 Englishz978311075405608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe Gruyte